          "1c_score": 6,
          "1c_reason": "There is a clear intent to differentiate sections (Intro groove establishment, Verse foundation, Chorus peaks, Bridge valley with wave, Chorus2 maximum intensity). However, the routine is stated as only 8x8 total while also mapping to the full song structure through Outro, and the Outro (65-72) is not actually choreographed—so the arc is conceptually described but not fully realized in actual counts coverage.",
          "2a_score": 4,
          "2a_reason": "Core Locking vocabulary is strong (Point, Scooby Doo, Which-a-way, Wrist roll, Stop & Go, locks, Up lock, Funky guitar), but several items drift from “pure Locking” or are non-standard/ambiguous: extended body wave across multiple counts, “head lock” as a named element, and “knee drop” (more hip-hop/freestyle unless clearly framed as Locking-style drop). The routine sometimes reads like mixing in generic funk/HH textures rather than strictly Locking technique.",
          "2b_score": 4,
          "2b_reason": "Many counts include direction, body parts, and holds, making it mostly teachable. But several passages are overloaded or underspecified for execution at 115 BPM (e.g., count 50 ‘4 points in 2 beats’ but placed on a single count; count 51 ‘full rotation’ in one count; count 59 layered events are plausible but need clearer footwork description). Some labels (Which-a-way stance shift, head lock) lack enough technical detail to reproduce consistently.",
          "2c_score": 3,
          "2c_reason": "There are multiple abrupt or physically tight transitions: jump + wrist roll on 52 then immediate knee lock with floor touch on 53; rapid multi-direction points compressed into count 50; full rotation Which-a-way in one count (51) followed by jump/wrist roll (52). Several sequences would require extra prep counts or simplified mechanics to be reliably clean at tempo.",
          "3a_score": 4,
          "3a_reason": "The choreography shows some creative musical ideas (cowbell-hit head accents, conga 16th chest isolations, riser embodied as arm rise, layered syncopation at count 59). However, much content relies on standard Locking blocks (point/which-a-way/funky guitar) and the novelty is more in description than in structurally new Locking phrasing.",
          "3b_score": 5,
          "3b_reason": "Good performance layering is described: facing changes (front/back), level changes (knee drop/floor touch/jump lock), spatial travel (diagonal Scooby Doo), and stated facial/eye focus intentions. Still, some of this is written as performance notes rather than being embedded as concrete, count-by-count staging throughout, and the ending/outro staging is incomplete.",
          "4a_score": 1,
